[30;1m53 | [0m[35m    def flush(self, client, path=None):[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35m        # This uses the linearity guarantee of zookeeper (and associated[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35m        # libraries) to create a temporary node, wait until a watcher notifies[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m        # it's created, then yield back for more work, and then at the end of[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m        # that work delete the created node. This ensures that the operations[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m        # done in the yield of this context manager will be applied and all[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m        # watchers will have fired before this context manager exits.[0m

[30;1m101 | [0m[35m   the given timeout the task is considered as timed-out and a timeout[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35m   exception is raised.[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35m3. A worker receives a request message and starts a new thread for processing[0m
[30;1m104 | [0m[35m   it.[0m

[30;1m81 | [0m[35mOf course these kind of features can come with some drawbacks:[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35m* The downside of decoupling the *how* and the *what* is that the imperative[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35m  model where functions control & manipulate state must start to be shifted[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35m  away from (and this is likely a mindset change for programmers used to the[0m

[30;1m58 | [0m[35m* Enhancing reliability: Decoupling of state alterations from what should be[0m

[30;1m60 | [0m[35m  track the current state and know at which point a workflow is in and how to[0m

[30;1m13 | [0m[35mTaskFlow provides different implementations of engines. Some may be easier to[0m
